Docker Image Vulnerability Scanning with Clair
Objectives
Deploy a Clair vulnerability scanner (a service that inspects container image layers against a CVE database) backed by PostgreSQL on a self-configured Ubuntu host
Build and scan Docker images of varying security posture, producing structured JSON reports that quantify vulnerabilities by severity
Integrate automated scanning into a registry-push workflow so every new image is scanned without manual intervention
Prerequisites
Comfort with Ubuntu command-line administration, including package management and file editing
Familiarity with Docker concepts: images, layers, registries, and Compose service definitions
Basic understanding of CI/CD pipeline concepts and JSON data structures
Lab Environment
You will work on a dedicated AWS EC2 Ubuntu instance provided by Al Nafi. The instance has a base Ubuntu installation; you will install all required tools in Task 1.

Task 1: Install and Verify the Full Toolchain
Step 1.1 â Install Docker Engine, Docker Compose, and supporting utilities
Install Docker Engine from the official Docker apt repository, then install Docker Compose v2 as a plugin, and finally install jq (a command-line JSON processor), curl, and wget.

sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install -y ca-certificates curl gnupg lsb-release jq wget python3 python3-pip

sudo install -m 0755 -d /etc/apt/keyrings
curl -fsSL https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu/gpg \
  | sudo gpg --dearmor -o /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg
sudo chmod a+r /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg

sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list <<'EOF'
deb [arch=amd64 signed-by=/etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg] https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu jammy stable
EOF

sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install -y docker-ce docker-ce-cli containerd.io docker-buildx-plugin docker-compose-plugin

sudo usermod -aG docker "$USER"
newgrp docker
Official guide if the URL above changes: https://docs.docker.com/engine/install/ubuntu/

